<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-subspaces" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Subspaces</title>

<definition xml:id="def-subspace">
<statement>
<p>
A subset <m>S\subseteq \R^n</m> is a <term>subspace</term> of <m>\R^n</m> if
<ol>

  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>\vect{0}\in S</m>,
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>\vect{u},\vect{v}\in S\implies \vect{u}+\vect{v}\in S</m>, and
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>\vect{u}\in S, \, c\in \R\implies c\vect{u}\in S.</m>
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<remark xml:id="rem-subspaces">
<statement>
<p>
<ul>

  <li>
  <p> 
  If <m>S</m> satisfies condition 2 above we say that <term><m>S</m> is closed under
  addition</term>, and if <m>S</m> satisfies condition 3 above, we say that 
  <term><m>S</m> is closed under scalar multiplication</term>.
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  As an exercise, show that if <m>S</m> is a subspace, then <m>S</m> is a vector space
  under the usual vector addition and scalar multiplication from <m>\R^n</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  As an exercise, show that <m>S</m> is a subspace as defined above if and only if 
  <md>
  S\not=\emptyset,\text{ and }a\vect{u}+b\vect{v}\in S\text{ for all }\vect{u},\vect{v}\in S,\,
  a,b\in \R.
  </md>
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  All of the definitions/concepts above work for subspaces of general vector spaces <m>V</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ul>
</p>
</statement>
</remark>

<example xml:id="ex-non-subspaces">
<statement>
<p>
Consider the subsets of <m>\R^2</m>:
<md>
<mrow>
\amp S_1 :=\{[x,y] : x+y >0\} \\
\amp S_2 := \{[x,] : x+y\ge 0\}\\
\amp S_3 := \{[x,y] : xy\ge 0\}.
</mrow>
</md>
We claim that none of the subsets are subspaces of <m>\R^2</m>. 
</p>
<p>
Since <m>0+0\not> 0</m>, <m>\vect{0}\not\in S_1</m>, and so <m>S_1</m> is not a subspace.
</p>

<p>
We have <m>\vect{0}\in S_2</m>. But, for instance, <m>[1,1]\in S_2</m> and <m>-2\in\R</m>, and
<md>
-2[1,1]=[-2,-2]\not\in S_2.
</md>
So <m>S_2</m> is not closed under scalar multiplication, and hence is not a subspace. 
</p>

<p>
Note that we have <m>[1,5],[-2,-2]\in S_3</m>, but 
<md>
[1,5]+[-2,-2]=[-1,3]\not\in S_3.
</md>
So <m>S_3</m> is not closed under addition, and hence is not a subspace.
</p>

</statement>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-subspace">
<statement>
<p>
Show that 
<md>
S:=\{[x,y,z]\in\R^3 : 2x-y+5z=0\}
</md>
is a subspace of <m>\R^3</m>.
</p>

<p>
We check the three condition of <xref ref="def-subspace"/>.
<ol>

  <li>
  <p> 
  Since <m>2(0)-0+5(0)=0</m> we have <m>\vect{0}\in S</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p>
  Let <m>[x_1,y_1,z_1],[x_2,y_2,z_2]\in S</m>. Then by definition we know that 
  <md>
  2x_1-y_1+5z_1=0=2x_2-y_2+5z_2.
  </md>
  Hence
<md>
<mrow>
\amp 2(x_1+x_2) - (y_1+y_2)+5(z_1+z_2) \\
\amp \qquad= (2x_1-y_1+5z_1)+(2x_2-y_2+5z_2) \\
\amp \qquad= 0+ 0\\
\amp \qquad= 0
</mrow>
</md>.
Hence <m>[x_1,y_1,z_1]+[x_2,y_2,z_2]\in S</m>, and so <m>S</m> is closed under addition.
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  Let <m>[x,y,z]\in S</m> and <m>c\in \R</m>. Then by definition we know that 
  <md>
  2x-y+5z=0.
  </md>
  Hence
<md>
<mrow>
2(cx) - (cy)+5(cz) \amp = c(2x-y+5z) \\
\amp = c(0)\\
\amp = 0
</mrow>
</md>.
Hence <m>c[x,y,z]\in S</m>, and so <m>S</m> is closed under scalar multiplication.
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ol>
</p>
<p>
Hence <m>S</m> is a subspace.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<remark xml:id="rem-planes-through-origin">
<statement>
<p>
Note that <m>S</m> is the plane <m> 2x-y+5z=0</m>. As an exercise, show that 
any other subset of the form 
<md>
\{[x,y,z]\in\R^3 : 2x-y+5z=a\}
</md>
for  <m>a\not=0</m> is not a subspace (i.e. planes parallel to <m>S</m> but not passing through 
the origin are not subspaces). This is true in general:
</p>
</statement>
</remark>

<theorem xml:id="thm-form-of-subspaces">
<statement>
<p>
<ol>

  <li>
  <p> 
  The only subspaces of <m>\R^2</m> are
  <ul>

  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>\{\vect{0}\},\R^2</m>, and
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  lines through the origin.
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ul>
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  The only subspaces of <m>\R^3</m> are
  <ul>

  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>\{\vect{0}\},\R^3</m>,
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  lines through the origin, and
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  planes through the origin.
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ul>
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<p>
You can imagine how these statements extend to subspaces of <m>\R^n</m>.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-spans-are-subspaces">
<statement>
<p>
For any <m>S=\{\vect{v}_1,\dots,\vect{v}_k\}\subseteq \R^n</m>, <m>\lspan(S)</m> is 
a subspace of <m>\R^n</m>.
</p>
</statement>

<proof>
<p>
We check the three conditions:
<ol>

  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>\vect{0}\in S</m> since <m>\vect{0}=0\vect{v}_1+\cdots + 0\vect{v}_k</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  If <m>\vect{u}=\sum_{i=1}^ka_i\vect{v}_i,\,\vect{v}=\sum_{i=1}^kb_i\vect{v}_i\in\lspan(S)</m>,
  then we have
  <md>
  \vect{u}+\vect{v}=\left(\sum_{i=1}^ka_i\vect{v}_i\right) + \left(\sum_{i=1}^kb_i\vect{v}_i\right)
  =\sum_{i=1}^k(a_i+b_i)\vect{v}_i\in \lspan(S).
  </md>
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  If <m>\vect{u}=\sum_{i=1}^ka_i\vect{v}_i\in\lspan(S)</m> and <m>c\in\R</m>,
  then we have
  <md>
  c\vect{u}=c\left(\sum_{i=1}^ka_i\vect{v}_i\right) 
  =\sum_{i=1}^k(ca_i)\vect{v}_i\in \lspan(S).
  </md>
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ol>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>

</section>